Commutative ring spectra

Birgit Richter Fachbereich Mathematik der UniversitÃ¤t Hamburg, BundesstraÃŸe 55, 20146 Hamburg, Germany richter@math.uni-hamburg.de http://www.math.uni-hamburg.de/home/richter/
Abstract.

In this survey paper on commutative ring spectra we present some basic features of commutative ring spectra and discuss model category structures. As a first interesting class of examples of such ring spectra we focus on (commutative) algebra spectra over commutative Eilenberg-Macâ€‰Lane ring spectra. We present two constructions that yield commutative ring spectra: Thom spectra associated to infinite loop maps and Segalâ€™s construction starting with bipermutative categories. We define topological Hochschild homology, some of its variants, and topological AndrÃ©-Quillen homology. Obstruction theory for commutative structures on ring spectra is described in two versions. The notion of Ã©tale extensions in the spectral world is tricky and we explain why. We define Picard groups and Brauer groups of commutative ring spectra and present examples.

Key words and phrases:
Commutative ring spectra, Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-structures on ring spectra, obstruction theory, units of ring spectra, Thom spectra, topological Hochschild homology, topological AndrÃ©-Quillen homology, Ã©tale maps, descent

1. Introduction

Since the 1990â€™s we have several symmetric monoidal categories of spectra at our disposal whose homotopy category is the stable homotopy category. The monoidal structure is usually denoted by âˆ§\wedge and is called the smash product of spectra. So since then we can talk about commutative objects in any of these categories â€“ these are commutative ring spectra. Even before such symmetric monoidal categories were constructed, the consequences of their existence were described. In [122, Â§2] Friedhelm Waldhausen outlines the role of â€˜rings up to homotopyâ€™. He also coined the expression â€˜brave new ringsâ€™ in a 1988 talk at Northwestern.

So what is the problem? Why donâ€™t we just write down nice commutative models of our favorite homotopy types and are down with it? Why does it make sense to have a whole chapter about this topic?

In algebra, if someone tells you to check whether a given ring is commutative, then you can sit down and check the axiom for commutativity and you should be fine. In stable homotopy theory the problem is more involved, since strict commutativity may only be satisfied by some preferred point set level model of the underlying associative ring spectrum and the operadic incarnation of commutativity is an extra structure rather than a condition.

There is one class of commutative ring spectra that is easy to construct. If you take singular cohomology with coefficients in a commutative ring Rğ‘…R, then this is represented by the Eilenberg-MacLane spectrum ğ»ğ‘…ğ»ğ‘…\mathit{HR} and this can be represented by a commutative ring spectrum.

So it would be nice if we could have explicit models for other homotopy types that come naturally equipped with a commutative ring structure. Sometimes this is possible. If you are interested in real (or complex) vector bundles over your space, then you want to understand real (or complex) topological K-theory and Michael Joachim [56] for instance produced an explicit analytically flavoured model for periodic real topological K-theory as a commutative ring spectrum in the setting of symmetric spectra [54].

There are a few general constructions that produce commutative ring spectra for you. For instance, the construction of Thom spectra often gives rise to commutative ring spectra. We will discuss this important class of examples in Section 4. A classical construction due to Graeme Segal also produces small nice models of commutative ring spectra (see Section 5).

Quite often, however, the spectra that we like are constructed in a synthetic way: You have some commutative ring spectrum Rğ‘…R and you kill a regular sequence of elements in its graded commutative ring of homotopy groups, (x1,x2,â€¦)subscriptğ‘¥1subscriptğ‘¥2â€¦(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots), xiâˆˆÏ€âˆ—â€‹(R)subscriptğ‘¥ğ‘–subscriptğœ‹ğ‘…x_{i}\in\pi_{*}(R), and you consider a spectrum Eğ¸E with homotopy groups Ï€âˆ—â€‹(E)â‰…Ï€âˆ—â€‹(R)/(x1,x2,â€¦)subscriptğœ‹ğ¸subscriptğœ‹ğ‘…subscriptğ‘¥1subscriptğ‘¥2â€¦\pi_{*}(E)\cong\pi_{*}(R)/(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots). Then it is not clear that Eğ¸E is a commutative ring spectrum.

A notorious example is the Brown-Peterson spectrum, ğµğ‘ƒğµğ‘ƒ\mathit{BP}. Take the complex cobordism spectrum ğ‘€ğ‘ˆğ‘€ğ‘ˆ\mathit{MU}. Its homotopy groups are

Ï€âˆ—â€‹(ğ‘€ğ‘ˆ)=â„¤â€‹[x1,x2,â€¦]subscriptğœ‹ğ‘€ğ‘ˆâ„¤subscriptğ‘¥1subscriptğ‘¥2â€¦\pi_{*}(\mathit{MU})=\mathbb{Z}[x_{1},x_{2},\ldots]

with xisubscriptğ‘¥ğ‘–x_{i} being a generator in degree 2â€‹i2ğ‘–2i. If you fix a large even degree, then you have a lot of possible elements in that degree, so you might wish to consider a spectrum with sparser homotopy groups. Using the theory of (commutative, 111-dimensional) formal group laws you can do that: If you consider a prime pğ‘p, then there is a spectrum, called the Brown-Peterson spectrum, that corresponds to pğ‘p-typical formal group laws. It can be realized as the image of an idempotent on ğ‘€ğ‘ˆğ‘€ğ‘ˆ\mathit{MU} and has

Ï€âˆ—â€‹(ğµğ‘ƒ)â‰…â„¤(p)â€‹[v1,v2,â€¦]subscriptğœ‹ğµğ‘ƒsubscriptâ„¤ğ‘subscriptğ‘£1subscriptğ‘£2â€¦\pi_{*}(\mathit{BP})\cong\mathbb{Z}_{(p)}[v_{1},v_{2},\ldots]

but now the algebraic generators are spread out in an exponential manner: The degree of visubscriptğ‘£ğ‘–v_{i} is 2â€‹piâˆ’22superscriptğ‘ğ‘–22p^{i}-2. You can actually choose the visubscriptğ‘£ğ‘–v_{i} as the xpiâˆ’1subscriptğ‘¥superscriptğ‘ğ‘–1x_{p^{i}-1}, so you can think of ğµğ‘ƒğµğ‘ƒ\mathit{BP} as a quotient of ğ‘€ğ‘ˆğ‘€ğ‘ˆ\mathit{MU} in the above sense. Since its birth in 1966 [27] its multiplicative properties where an important issue. In [18] it was for instance shown that ğµğ‘ƒğµğ‘ƒ\mathit{BP} has some partial coherence for homotopy commutativity, but in 2017 Tyler Lawson finally shows that at the prime 222 at least, ğµğ‘ƒğµğ‘ƒ\mathit{BP} is not a commutative ring spectrum [61]!

There are even worse examples: If you take the sphere spectrum Sğ‘†S and you try to kill the non-regular element 2âˆˆÏ€0â€‹(S)2subscriptğœ‹0ğ‘†2\in\pi_{0}(S) then you get the mod-222-Moore spectrum. That isnâ€™t even a ring spectrum up to homotopy. You can also kill all the generators viâˆˆÏ€âˆ—â€‹(Bâ€‹P)subscriptğ‘£ğ‘–subscriptğœ‹ğµğ‘ƒv_{i}\in\pi_{*}(BP) including p=v0ğ‘subscriptğ‘£0p=v_{0} and leaving only one vnsubscriptğ‘£ğ‘›v_{n} alive. The resulting spectrum is the connective version of Morava K-theory, kâ€‹(n)ğ‘˜ğ‘›k(n). At the prime 222 this isnâ€™t even homotopy commutative. In fact, Urs WÃ¼rgler shows more [125]: If Ï€0subscriptğœ‹0\pi_{0} of a homotopy commutative ring spectrum has characteristic two, then it is a generalized Eilenberg-Macâ€‰Lane spectrum. Recent work of Mathew, Naumann and Noel puts severe restrictions on finite Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-ring spectra [79].

So how do you decide such questions? How can you determine whether a given spectrum is a commutative ring spectrum if you donâ€™t have a construction that tells you right away that it is commutative? This is where obstruction theory comes into the story.

There is an operadic notion of an Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-ring spectrum that goes back to Boardman-Vogt and May. Comparison theorems [76], [111] then tell you whether these more complicated objects are equivalent to commutative ring spectra. In the categories of symmetric spectra, orthogonal spectra and Sğ‘†S-modules they are.

Obstruction theory might help you with a decision whether a spectrum carries a commutative monoid structure: One version [16] gives obstructions for lifting the ordinary Postnikov tower to a Postnikov tower that lives within the category of commutative ring spectra. The other kind finds some obstruction classes that tell you that you cannot extend some partial bits and pieces of a nice multiplication to a fully fledged structure of an Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-ring spectrum or that some homology or homotopy operation that you observe contradicts such a structure. This can be used for a negative result (as in [61]) or for positive statements: There are result by Robinson [101] and Goerss-Hopkins [38, 39] that tell you that you have a (sometimes even unique) Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-ring structure on your spectrum if all the obstruction groups vanish. Most notably Goerss and Hopkins used obstruction theory to prove that the Morava stabilizer groups acts on the corresponding Lubin-Tate spectrum via Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-morphisms [38].

There are other things that are weird for commutative ring spectra. Quite often, we end up working with ideals in the graded commutative ring of homotopy groups, but as we saw above, this is not a suitable notion of ideal. There is a notion of an ideal in the context of (commutative) ring spectra [53] due to Jeff Smith, but still several algebraic constructions do not have an analogue in spectra.

The algebraic behaviour on the level of homotopy groups can be quite deceiving: complexification turns a real vector bundle into a complex vector bundle. This induces a map Ï€âˆ—â€‹(ğ¾ğ‘‚)â†’Ï€âˆ—â€‹(ğ¾ğ‘ˆ)â†’subscriptğœ‹ğ¾ğ‘‚subscriptğœ‹ğ¾ğ‘ˆ\pi_{*}(\mathit{KO})\rightarrow\pi_{*}(\mathit{KU}) which can be realized as a map of commutative ring spectra c:ğ¾ğ‘‚â†’ğ¾ğ‘ˆ:ğ‘â†’ğ¾ğ‘‚ğ¾ğ‘ˆc\colon\mathit{KO}\rightarrow\mathit{KU}. On homotopy groups we get

Even for ordinary rings, viewing a (commutative) ring Rğ‘…R as a (commutative) ring spectrum via the Eilenberg-Macâ€‰Lane spectrum functor changes the situation completely. The ring Rğ‘…R has a characteristic map Ï‡:â„¤â†’R:ğœ’â†’â„¤ğ‘…\chi\colon\mathbb{Z}\rightarrow R because the integers are the initial ring. As a ring spectrum, Hâ€‹â„¤ğ»â„¤H\mathbb{Z} is far from being initial. The map Hâ€‹Ï‡ğ»ğœ’H\chi can be precomposed with the unit map of Hâ€‹â„¤ğ»â„¤H\mathbb{Z}

and the sphere spectrum Sğ‘†S is the initial ring spectrum! Now there is a lot of space between the sphere and any ring. I will discuss two consequences that this has: There is actually algebraic geometry happening between the sphere spectrum and the prime field ğ”½psubscriptğ”½ğ‘\mathbb{F}_{p}: There is a Galois extension of commutative ring spectra (see 8.1) Aâ†’Hâ€‹ğ”½pâ†’ğ´ğ»subscriptğ”½ğ‘A\rightarrow H\mathbb{F}_{p}!

Another feature is that there exist differential graded algebras Aâˆ—subscriptğ´A_{*} and Bâˆ—subscriptğµB_{*} that are not quasi-isomorphic, but whose associated algebra spectra over an Eilenberg-Macâ€‰Lane spectrum [117] are equivalent as ring spectra [31]. Similar phenomena happen if you consider differential graded Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-algebras: There are non quasi-isomorphic ones whose associated commutative algebras over an Eilenberg-Macâ€‰Lane spectrum [98] are equivalent as commutative ring spectra [21].

Content

The structure of this overview is as follows: We start with some basic features of commutative ring spectra and their model category structures in Section 2. The most basic way to relate classical algebra to brave new algebra is via the Eilenberg-Macâ€‰Lane spectrum functor. We study chain algebras and algebras over Eilenberg-Macâ€‰Lane ring spectra in Section 3. As you can study the group of units of a ring we consider units of ring spectra and Thom spectra in Section 4. In Section 5 we present a construction going back to Segal. Plugging in a bipermutative category yields a commutative ring spectrum.

In Section 6 we introduce topological Hochschild homology and some of its variants and topological AndrÃ©-Quillen homology. In Section 7 we discuss some versions of obstruction theory that tell you whether a given multiplicative cohomology theory can be represented by a strict commutative model.

Some concepts from algebra translate directly to spectra but some others donâ€™t. We discuss the different concepts of Ã©tale maps for commutative algebra spectra in Section 8. Picard and Brauer groups for commutative ring spectra are important invariants and feature in Section 9.

Disclaimers

For more than 30 years, the phrase commutative ring spectrum meant a commutative monoid in the homotopy category of spectra. Since the 90â€™s this has changed. At the beginning of this new era people were careful not to use this name, in order to avoid confusion with the homotopy version. In this paper we reserve the phrase commutative ring spectrum for a commutative monoid in some symmetric monoidal category of spectra.

The second disclaimer is that for this paper a space is always compactly generated weak Hausdorff. I denote the corresponding category just by ğ–³ğ—ˆğ—‰ğ–³ğ—ˆğ—‰\mathsf{Top}.

Last but not least: Of course, this overview is not complete. I had to omit important aspects of the field due to space constraints. Most prominently probably is the omission of not discussing topological cyclic homology and its wonderful applications to algebraic K-theory.

I try to give adequate references, but often it was just not feasible to describe the whole development of a topic and much worse, I probably have forgotten to cite important contributions. If you read this and it affects you, then I can only apologize.

2. Features of commutative ring spectra

2.1. Some basics

Before we actually start with model structures, we state some basic facts about commutative ring spectra.

Let Rğ‘…R be a commutative ring spectrum. Then the category of Rğ‘…R-module spectra is closed symmetric monoidal: For two such Rğ‘…R-module spectra M,Nğ‘€ğ‘M,N the smash product over Rğ‘…R, Mâˆ§RNsubscriptğ‘…ğ‘€ğ‘M\wedge_{R}N, is again an Rğ‘…R-module and the usual axioms of a symmetric monoidal category are satisfied. There is an Rğ‘…R-module spectrum FRâ€‹(M,N)subscriptğ¹ğ‘…ğ‘€ğ‘F_{R}(M,N), the function spectrum of Rğ‘…R-module maps from Mğ‘€M to Nğ‘N.

We denote the category of Rğ‘…R-module spectra by â„³Rsubscriptâ„³ğ‘…\mathcal{M}_{R}. The category of commutative Rğ‘…R-algebras is the category of commutative monoids in â„³Rsubscriptâ„³ğ‘…\mathcal{M}_{R} and we denote this category by ğ’Rsubscriptğ’ğ‘…\mathcal{C}_{R}.

By definition, every object Ağ´A of ğ’Rsubscriptğ’ğ‘…\mathcal{C}_{R} receives a unit map from Rğ‘…R and hence Rğ‘…R is initial in ğ’Rsubscriptğ’ğ‘…\mathcal{C}_{R}. In particular, the sphere spectrum is the initial commutative ring spectrum. Every discrete ring is a â„¤â„¤\mathbb{Z}-algebra, similarly, every (commutative) ring spectrum is a (commutative) Sğ‘†S-algebra. If Rğ‘…R is a commutative ring spectrum, then the category of commutative Rğ‘…R-algebra is isomorphic to the category of commutative ring spectra under Rğ‘…R, i.e., such commutative ring spectra Ağ´A with a distinguished map Î·:Râ†’A:ğœ‚â†’ğ‘…ğ´\eta\colon R\rightarrow A in that category.

We allow the trivial Rğ‘…R-algebra corresponding to the one-point spectrum âˆ—âˆ—\ast and this spectrum is a terminal object in ğ’Rsubscriptğ’ğ‘…\mathcal{C}_{R}.

In any symmetric monoidal category (ğ’,âŠ—,1,Ï„)ğ’tensor-product1ğœ(\mathcal{C},\otimes,1,\tau) the coproduct of two commutative monoids Ağ´A and BğµB in ğ’ğ’\mathcal{C} is AâŠ—Btensor-productğ´ğµA\otimes B. So, for two commutative Rğ‘…R-algebras Ağ´A and BğµB, their coproduct is Aâˆ§RBsubscriptğ‘…ğ´ğµA\wedge_{R}B.

2.2. Model structures on commutative monoids

I will assume that you are familiar with the concept of model categories and that you have seen some examples and read Chapter 4 in this book. Good general reference are Hoveyâ€™s [52] or Hirschhornâ€™s [48] book. You could also just skip this section and have in mind that there are some serious model category issues lurking in the dark.

For this section I will mainly focus on two models for spectra: Symmetric spectra [54] and Sğ‘†S-modules [34]. They are different concerning their model structures. In the model structure in [54] on symmetric spectra the sphere spectrum is cofibrant whereas in the one for Sğ‘†S-modules it is not, but all objects are fibrant.

The model structures on commutative monoids in either of the categories [34, 54] are special cases of a right induced model structure: We have a functor PRsubscriptğ‘ƒğ‘…P_{R} from Rğ‘…R-module spectra to commutative Rğ‘…R-algebra spectra assigning the free commutative Rğ‘…R-algebra spectrum on Mğ‘€M to any Rğ‘…R-module spectrum Mğ‘€M, explicitly

PRâ€‹(M)=â‹nâ©¾0Mâˆ§Rn/Î£n.subscriptğ‘ƒğ‘…ğ‘€subscriptğ‘›0superscriptğ‘€subscriptğ‘…ğ‘›subscriptÎ£ğ‘›P_{R}(M)=\bigvee_{n\geqslant 0}M^{\wedge_{R}n}/\Sigma_{n}.

The symbol PRsubscriptğ‘ƒğ‘…P_{R} should remind you of a polynomial algebra. This functor has a right adjoint, the forgetful functor Uğ‘ˆU. In a right-induced model structure one determines the fibrations and weak equivalences by the right adjoint functor. In our cases, a map of commutative Rğ‘…R-algebra spectra is a fibration or a weak equivalence, if it is one in the underlying category of Rğ‘…R-module spectra. Note that establishing right induced model structures on commutative monoids in some model category does not always work. The standard example is the category of ğ”½psubscriptğ”½ğ‘\mathbb{F}_{p}-chain complexes (say pğ‘p is an odd prime). Then the chain complex ğ”»2superscriptğ”»2\mathbb{D}^{2} is acyclic, having ğ”½psubscriptğ”½ğ‘\mathbb{F}_{p} in degrees 111 and 222 with the identity map as differential, but the free graded commutative monoid generated by it is Î›ğ”½pâ€‹(x1)âŠ—ğ”½pâ€‹[x2]tensor-productsubscriptÎ›subscriptğ”½ğ‘subscriptğ‘¥1subscriptğ”½ğ‘delimited-[]subscriptğ‘¥2\Lambda_{\mathbb{F}_{p}}(x_{1})\otimes\mathbb{F}_{p}[x_{2}] with |xi|=isubscriptğ‘¥ğ‘–ğ‘–|x_{i}|=i and the induced differential is determined by dâ€‹(x2)=x1ğ‘‘subscriptğ‘¥2subscriptğ‘¥1d(x_{2})=x_{1} and the Leibniz rule. But then dâ€‹(x2p)ğ‘‘superscriptsubscriptğ‘¥2ğ‘d(x_{2}^{p}) is a cycle that is not a boundary, so the resulting object is not acyclic.

If Rğ‘…R is a commutative Sğ‘†S-algebra in the setting of EKMM [34], then the categories of associative Rğ‘…R-algebras and of commutative Rğ‘…R-algebras possess a right induced model structure [34, Corollary VII.4.10]. The existence of the model structure for commutative monoids is a special case of the existence of right-induced model structures for ğ•‹ğ•‹\mathbb{T}-algebras ([34, Theorem VII.4.9]) where ğ•‹ğ•‹\mathbb{T} is a continuous monad on the category of Rğ‘…R-module spectra that preserves reflexive coequalizers and satisfies the cofibration hypothesis [34, VII.4]. The category of commutative Sğ‘†S-algebras is identified [34, Proposition II.4.5] with the category of algebras for the monad PSsubscriptğ‘ƒğ‘†P_{S} as above on the category of Sğ‘†S-modules.

In diagram categories such as symmetric spectra and orthogonal spectra the situation is different: In the standard model structures on these categories the sphere spectrum is cofibrant. If one would take a right-induced model structure on the category of commutative monoids, i.e., the model structure such that a map of commutative ring spectra f:Aâ†’B:ğ‘“â†’ğ´ğµf\colon A\rightarrow B is a fibration or weak equivalence if it is one in the underlying category, then the sphere would still be cofibrant. If we take a fibrant replacement of the sphere Sâ†’Sfibâ†’ğ‘†superscriptğ‘†fibS\rightarrow S^{\text{fib}}, then in particular Sfibsuperscriptğ‘†fibS^{\text{fib}} would be fibrant in the model category of symmetric spectra, hence it would be an Omega-spectrum and its zeroth level would be a strictly commutative model for Qâ€‹S0ğ‘„superscriptğ‘†0QS^{0}. However, Moore shows [90, Theorem 3.29] that this implied that Qâ€‹S0ğ‘„superscriptğ‘†0QS^{0} had the homotopy type of a product of Eilenberg-MacLane spaces â€“ but this is false.

The usual way to avoid this problem is to consider a positive model structure on Sâ€‹pÎ£ğ‘†superscriptğ‘Î£Sp^{\Sigma} (see [76, Definition 6.1] for the general approach). Here the positive level fibrations (weak equivalences) are maps fâˆˆSâ€‹pÎ£â€‹(X,Y)ğ‘“ğ‘†superscriptğ‘Î£ğ‘‹ğ‘Œf\in Sp^{\Sigma}(X,Y) such that fâ€‹(n)ğ‘“ğ‘›f(n) is a fibration (weak equivalence) for all levels nâ©¾1ğ‘›1n\geqslant 1. The positive cofibrations are then cofibrations in Sâ€‹pÎ£ğ‘†superscriptğ‘Î£Sp^{\Sigma} that are isomorphisms in level zero. The positive stable model category is then obtained by a Bousfield localization that forces the stable equivalences to be the weak equivalences and the right-induced model structure on the commutative monoids in Sâ€‹pÎ£ğ‘†superscriptğ‘Î£Sp^{\Sigma} then has the desired properties.

There is another nice model for connective spectra, given by Î“Î“\Gamma-spaces [114, 70]. This category is built out of functors from finite pointed sets to spaces, so it is a very hands-on category with explicit constructions. It is also a symmetric monoidal category with a suitable model structure. We refer to [70, 110] for background on this. Its (commutative) monoids are called (commutative) Î“Î“\Gamma-rings. Beware that commutative Î“Î“\Gamma-rings, however, do not model all connective commutative ring spectra. Tyler Lawson proves in [62] that commutative Î“Î“\Gamma-rings satisfy a vanishing condition for Dyer-Lashof operations of positive degree on classes in their zeroth mod-pğ‘p-homology (for all primes pğ‘p) and that for instance the free Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-ring spectrum generated by ğ•Š0superscriptğ•Š0\mathbb{S}^{0} cannot be modelled as a commutative Î“Î“\Gamma-ring.

2.3. Behaviour of the underlying modules

In the setting of EKMM it is shown that the underlying Rğ‘…R-modules of cofibrant commutative Rğ‘…R-algebras have a well-behaved smash product in the derived category of Rğ‘…R-modules:

Theorem 2.1.

[34, Theorem VII.6.7] â€‰ If Ağ´A and BğµB are two cofibrant commutative Rğ‘…R-algebras, and if and are chosen cell Rğ‘…R-module spectra approximations then

Ï†Aâˆ§RÏ†B:Î“â€‹Aâˆ§RÎ“â€‹Bâ†’Aâˆ§RB:subscriptğ‘…subscriptğœ‘ğ´subscriptğœ‘ğµâ†’subscriptğ‘…Î“ğ´Î“ğµsubscriptğ‘…ğ´ğµ\varphi_{A}\wedge_{R}\varphi_{B}\colon\Gamma A\wedge_{R}\Gamma B\rightarrow A\wedge_{R}B

is a weak equivalence.

Brooke Shipley developed a model structure for commutative symmetric ring spectra in [116] in which the underlying symmetric spectrum of a cofibrant commutative ring spectrum is also cofibrant as a symmetric spectrum [116, Corollary 4.3].

She starts with introducing a different model structure on symmetric spectra. Let Mğ‘€M denote the class of monomorphisms of symmetric sequences in pointed simplicial sets and let SâŠ—Mtensor-productğ‘†ğ‘€S\otimes M denote the set {SâŠ—f,fâˆˆM}tensor-productğ‘†ğ‘“ğ‘“ğ‘€\{S\otimes f,f\in M\} where âŠ—tensor-product\otimes denotes the tensor product of symmetric sequences. An Sğ‘†S-cofibration is a morphism in (SâŠ—M)tensor-productğ‘†ğ‘€(S\otimes M)-cof, i.e., a morphism in Sâ€‹pÎ£ğ‘†superscriptğ‘Î£Sp^{\Sigma} that has the left lifting property with respect to maps that have the right lifting property with respect to SâŠ—Mtensor-productğ‘†ğ‘€S\otimes M. She shows that the classes of Sğ‘†S-cofibrations and stable equivalences determine a model structure with the Sğ‘†S-fibrations being the class of morphisms with the right lifting property with respect to Sğ‘†S-cofibrations that are also stable equivalences [116, Theorem 2.4]. This model structure was already mentioned in [54, 5.3.6]. Shipley proves that this model structure is cofibrantly generated, is monoidal and satisfies the monoid axiom [116, 2.4, 2.5].

Note that symmetric spectra are Sğ‘†S-modules in symmetric sequences. This allows for a version of an Rğ‘…R-model structure for every associative symmetric ring spectrum Rğ‘…R with Rğ‘…R-cofibrations, Rğ‘…R-fibrations and stable equivalences [116, Theorem 2.6]. In the positive variant of this model structure the positive Rğ‘…R-cofibrations are Rğ‘…R-cofibrations that are isomorphisms in level zero. Together with the stable equivalences this determines the positive Rğ‘…R-model structure.

The corresponding right induced model structure on commutative Rğ‘…R-algebra spectra for a commutative symmetric ring spectrum Rğ‘…R is then the convenient model structure: The weak equivalences are stable equivalences, the fibrations are positive Rğ‘…R-fibrations and the cofibrations are determined by the structure.

She then shows the remarkable property of this model structure on commutative Rğ‘…R-algebra spectra:

Theorem 2.2.

[116, Corollary 4.3] â€‰ If Ağ´A is cofibrant as a commutative Rğ‘…R-algebra then Ağ´A is Rğ‘…R-cofibrant in the Rğ‘…R-model structure. If Ağ´A is fibrant as a commutative Rğ‘…R-algebra, then Ağ´A is fibrant in the positive Rğ‘…R-model structure on Rğ‘…R-module spectra.

The positive Rğ‘…R-model structure ensures that Rğ‘…R is not cofibrant, hence cofibrant commutative Rğ‘…R-algebras will not be positively Rğ‘…R-cofibrant!

2.4. Comparison, rigidification and Ensubscriptğ¸ğ‘›E_{n}-structures

Stefan Schwede proves [111, Theorem 5.1] that the homotopy category of commutative Sğ‘†S-algebras from [34] is equivalent to the homotopy category of commutative symmetric ring spectra by establishing a Quillen equivalence between the corresponding model categories. In [76, Theorem 0.7] the analogous comparison result is proven for commutative orthogonal ring spectra and commutative symmetric ring spectra.

Even before any symmetric monoidal category of spectra was constructed, the notion of operadically defined Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-ring spectra [81] was available. An Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-structure on a spectrum is a multiplication that is homotopy commutative in a coherent way. See Chapter 5 of this book for background on operads and their role in the study of spectra with additional structure.

There is an explicit comparison of the good old Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-ring spectra and commutative ring spectra, see [34, Proposition II.4.5] or [76, Remark 0.14], in particular, every Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-ring spectrum R~~ğ‘…\tilde{R} can be rigidified to a commutative ring spectrum Rğ‘…R in such a way that the homotopy type is preserved.

There are several popular Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-operads that will show up later: for instance the linear isometries operad (see (4.3)) and the Barratt-Eccles operad. The nğ‘›n-ary part of the latter is easy to describe: You take ğ’ªâ€‹(n)=Eâ€‹Î£nğ’ªğ‘›ğ¸subscriptÎ£ğ‘›\mathcal{O}(n)=E\Sigma_{n}, a contractible space with free Î£nsubscriptÎ£ğ‘›\Sigma_{n}-action. For compatiblity reasons it is advisible to take the realization of the standard simplicial model of Eâ€‹Î£nğ¸subscriptÎ£ğ‘›E\Sigma_{n} whose set of qğ‘q-simplices is (Î£n)q+1superscriptsubscriptÎ£ğ‘›ğ‘1(\Sigma_{n})^{q+1}.

An operad with a nice geometric description is the little mğ‘šm-cubes operad, that in arity nğ‘›n consists of the space of nğ‘›n-tuples of linearly embedded mğ‘šm-cubes in the standard mğ‘šm-cube with disjoint interiors and with axes parallel to that of the ambient cube. [23, Example 5]. We call this (and every equivalent) operad in spaces Emsubscriptğ¸ğ‘šE_{m}. For m=1ğ‘š1m=1 this operad parametrizes Aâˆsubscriptğ´A_{\infty}-structures and the colimit is an Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-operad. Hence the intermediate Emsubscriptğ¸ğ‘šE_{m}â€™s for 1<m<âˆ1ğ‘š1<m<\infty interpolate between these structures, they give Aâˆsubscriptğ´A_{\infty}-structures with homotopy-commutative multiplications that are coherent up to some order.

3. Chain algebras and algebras over Eilenberg-Macâ€‰Lane spectra

The derived category of a ring is an important object in many subjects. The initial ring is the ring of integers. Every ring Rğ‘…R has an associated Eilenberg-Macâ€‰Lane spectrum, ğ»ğ‘…ğ»ğ‘…\mathit{HR}.

3.1. ğ»ğ‘…ğ»ğ‘…\mathit{HR}-module and algebra spectra

We collect some results that compare the category of chain complexes of Rğ‘…R-modules with the category of module spectra over ğ»ğ‘…ğ»ğ‘…\mathit{HR}. We start with additive statements and move to comparison results for flavors of differential graded Rğ‘…R-algebras. For an overview of algebraic applications of these equivalences see for instance [41].

In the eighties, so before any strict symmetric monoidal category of spectra was constructed, Alan Robinson developed the notion of the derived category, ğ’Ÿâ€‹(E)ğ’Ÿğ¸\mathcal{D}(E), of right Eğ¸E-module spectra for every Aâˆsubscriptğ´A_{\infty}-ring spectrum Eğ¸E. He showed the following result.

Theorem 3.1.

[99, Theorem 3.1] â€‰ For every associative ring Rğ‘…R there is an equivalence of categories between the derived category of Rğ‘…R, ğ’Ÿâ€‹(R)ğ’Ÿğ‘…\mathcal{D}(R), and the derived category of the associated Eilenberg-Macâ€‰Lane spectrum, ğ’Ÿâ€‹(ğ»ğ‘…)ğ’Ÿğ»ğ‘…\mathcal{D}(\mathit{HR}).

Later, in the context of Sğ‘†S-modules this corresponds to [34, IV, Theorem 2.4]. Work of Schwede and Shipley strengthened the result to a Quillen equivalence of the corresponding model categories:

Theorem 3.2.

[113, Theorem 5.1.6] â€‰ The model category of unbounded chain complexes of Rğ‘…R-modules is Quillen equivalent to the model category of ğ»ğ‘…ğ»ğ‘…\mathit{HR}-module spectra.

Stefan Schwede uses the setting of Î“Î“\Gamma-spaces [110] to embed simplicial rings and modules into the stable world: He constructs a lax symmetric monoidal Eilenberg-Macâ€‰Lane functor Hğ»H from simplicial abelian groups to Î“Î“\Gamma-spaces together with a linearization functor Lğ¿L in the opposite direction and proves the following comparison result:

Theorem 3.3.

[110, Theorems 4.4, 4.5] â€‰ If Rğ‘…R is a simplicial ring, then the adjoint functors Hğ»H and Lğ¿L constitute a Quillen equivalence between the categories of simplicial Rğ‘…R-modules and ğ»ğ‘…ğ»ğ‘…\mathit{HR}-module spectra. If Rğ‘…R is in addition commutative, then Hğ»H and Lğ¿L induce a Quillen equivalence between the categories of simplicial Rğ‘…R-algebras and ğ»ğ‘…ğ»ğ‘…\mathit{HR}-algebra spectra.

Here, the functor Lğ¿L is actually left inverse to Hğ»H and induces an isomorphism of Î“Î“\Gamma-spaces

ğ–§ğ—ˆğ—†â€‹(Hâ€‹A,Hâ€‹B)â‰…Hâ€‹(ğ–§ğ—ˆğ—†ğ—Œğ– ğ–»â€‹(A,B))ğ–§ğ—ˆğ—†ğ»ğ´ğ»ğµğ»subscriptğ–§ğ—ˆğ—†ğ—Œğ– ğ–»ğ´ğµ\mathsf{Hom}(HA,HB)\cong H(\mathsf{Hom}_{\mathsf{sAb}}(A,B))

[110, Lemma 2.1], thus Hğ»H embeds algebra into brave new algebra.

Brooke Shipley extends this equivalence to corresponding categories of monoids in the differential graded setting:

Theorem 3.4.

[117, Theorem 1.1] â€‰ For any commutative ring Rğ‘…R, the model categories of unbounded differential graded Rğ‘…R-algebras and ğ»ğ‘…ğ»ğ‘…\mathit{HR}-algebra spectra are Quillen equivalent.

Dugger and Shipley show in [31] that there are examples of ğ»ğ‘…ğ»ğ‘…\mathit{HR}-algebras that are weakly equivalent as Sğ‘†S-algebras, but that are not quasi-isomorphic. A concrete example is the differential graded ring Aâˆ—subscriptğ´A_{*} which is generated by an element in degree 111, e1subscriptğ‘’1e_{1}, and has dâ€‹(e1)=2ğ‘‘subscriptğ‘’12d(e_{1})=2 and satisfies e14=0superscriptsubscriptğ‘’140e_{1}^{4}=0. You find more examples and proofs in [31, Â§Â§4,5].

We cannot expect that commutative ğ»ğ‘…ğ»ğ‘…\mathit{HR}-algebra spectra correspond to commutative differential graded Rğ‘…R-algebras unless Rğ‘…R is of characteristic zero, because of cohomology operations, but we get the following result:

Theorem 3.5.

[98, Corollary 8.3] â€‰ Let Rğ‘…R be a commutative ring. Then there is a chain of Quillen equivalences between the model category of commutative ğ»ğ‘…ğ»ğ‘…\mathit{HR}-algebra spectra and Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-monoids in the category of unbounded Rğ‘…R-chain complexes.

Haldun Ã–zgÃ¼r BayÄ±ndÄ±r shows [21] that one can find Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-differential graded algebras that are not quasi-isomorphic, but whose corresponding commutative ğ»ğ‘…ğ»ğ‘…\mathit{HR}-algebra spectra are equivalent as commutative ring spectra.

3.2. Cochain algebras

A prominent class of examples of commutative ğ»ğ‘…ğ»ğ‘…\mathit{HR}-algebra spectra consists of function spectra Fâ€‹(X+,ğ»ğ‘…)ğ¹subscriptğ‘‹ğ»ğ‘…F(X_{+},\mathit{HR}). Here, Xğ‘‹X is an arbitrary space and Rğ‘…R is a commutative ring. The diagonal Î”:Xâ†’XÃ—X:Î”â†’ğ‘‹ğ‘‹ğ‘‹\Delta\colon X\rightarrow X\times X and the multiplication on ğ»ğ‘…ğ»ğ‘…\mathit{HR}, Î¼ğ»ğ‘…subscriptğœ‡ğ»ğ‘…\mu_{\mathit{HR}}, induce a multiplication

that turns Fâ€‹(X+,ğ»ğ‘…)ğ¹subscriptğ‘‹ğ»ğ‘…F(X_{+},\mathit{HR}) into a ğ»ğ‘…ğ»ğ‘…\mathit{HR}-algebra spectrum. As the diagonal is cocommutative and as Î¼ğ»ğ‘…subscriptğœ‡ğ»ğ‘…\mu_{\mathit{HR}} is commutative, the resulting multiplication is commutative.

These function spectra are models for the singular cochains of a space Xğ‘‹X with coefficients in Rğ‘…R:

Ï€âˆ—â€‹(Fâ€‹(X+,ğ»ğ‘…))â‰…Hâˆ’âˆ—â€‹(X;R).subscriptğœ‹ğ¹subscriptğ‘‹ğ»ğ‘…superscriptğ»absentğ‘‹ğ‘…\pi_{*}(F(X_{+},\mathit{HR}))\cong H^{-*}(X;R).

Beware that the homotopy groups of Fâ€‹(X+,ğ»ğ‘…)ğ¹subscriptğ‘‹ğ»ğ‘…F(X_{+},\mathit{HR}) are concentrated in non-positive degrees â€“ i.e., Fâ€‹(X+,ğ»ğ‘…)ğ¹subscriptğ‘‹ğ»ğ‘…F(X_{+},\mathit{HR}) is coconnective.

Studying the singular cochains of a space Sâˆ—â€‹(X;R)superscriptğ‘†ğ‘‹ğ‘…S^{*}(X;R) as a differential graded Rğ‘…R-module is not enough in order to recover the homotopy type of Xğ‘‹X. If we work over the rational numbers, then Quillen showed that rational homotopy theory is algebraic in the sense that one can use rational differential graded Lie algebras or coalgebras as models for rational homotopy theory [94]. Sullivan [118] constructed a functor, assigning a rational differential graded commutative algebra to a space, that is closely related to the singular cochain functor with rational coefficients. He used this to classify rational homotopy types.

For a general commutative ring Rğ‘…R, the singular cochains are an Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-algebra. Mike Mandell proves [72, Main Theorem] that the singular cochain functor with coefficients in an algebraic closure of ğ”½psubscriptğ”½ğ‘\mathbb{F}_{p}, ğ”½Â¯psubscriptÂ¯ğ”½ğ‘\bar{\mathbb{F}}_{p}, induces an equivalence between the homotopy category of connected pğ‘p-complete nilpotent spaces of finite pğ‘p-type and a full subcategory of the homotopy category of Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-ğ”½Â¯psubscriptÂ¯ğ”½ğ‘\bar{\mathbb{F}}_{p}-algebras. He also characterizes those Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-ğ”½Â¯psubscriptÂ¯ğ”½ğ‘\bar{\mathbb{F}}_{p}-algebras that arise as cochain algebras of 111-connected pğ‘p-complete spaces of finity pğ‘p-type explicitly [72, Characterization Theorem]. There is also an integral version of this result, stating that finite type nilpotent spaces are weakly equivalent if and only if their Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-algebras of integral cochains are quasi-isomorphic [74, Main Theorem].

4. Units of ring spectra and Thom spectra

One construction that can give rise to highly structured multiplications on a spectrum is the Thom spectrum construction: For instance, complex bordism, Mâ€‹Uğ‘€ğ‘ˆMU, obtains a commutative ring structure this way. 4.3. Graded units

There is one problem with the constructions of spaces and spectra of units as above. As they are constructed from the underlying infinite loop space of a spectrum and just take into account the units in Ï€0subscriptğœ‹0\pi_{0}, they ignore graded units coming from periodicity elements in the homotopy groups of a spectrum. So for instance, the Bott class uâˆˆÏ€2â€‹(ğ¾ğ‘ˆ)ğ‘¢subscriptğœ‹2ğ¾ğ‘ˆu\in\pi_{2}(\mathit{KU}) is not represented in Gâ€‹L1â€‹(ğ¾ğ‘ˆ)ğºsubscriptğ¿1ğ¾ğ‘ˆGL_{1}(\mathit{KU}) or Gâ€‹L1Iâ€‹(ğ¾ğ‘ˆ)ğºsuperscriptsubscriptğ¿1ğ¼ğ¾ğ‘ˆGL_{1}^{I}(\mathit{KU}).

There is a construction of graded units. Weâ€™ll sketch the construction and mention two of its applications: graded Thom spectra and logarithmic ring spectra.

Remark 4.19.
  2. (a)

    John Rognes developed the concept of logarithmic ring spectra and in [106] and [105] this concept is fully explored with the help of graded units. The idea is that you want a spectrum that sits between a commutative ring spectrum like kâ€‹uğ‘˜ğ‘¢ku and its localization ğ¾ğ‘ˆğ¾ğ‘ˆ\mathit{KU}, so you remember the Bott class as the extra datum of a logarithmic structure. This concept has its origin in algebraic geometry and is useful in stable homotopy theory for instance for obtaining localization sequences in topological Hochschild homology [105].

  3. (b)

    In [108] Sagave and Schlichtkrull use graded units adapted to the setting of orthogonal spectra, Gâ€‹L1Wğºsuperscriptsubscriptğ¿1ğ‘ŠGL_{1}^{W}, to construct graded Thom spectra associated to virtual vector bundles, i.e., associated to a map f:Xâ†’â„¤Ã—Bâ€‹O:ğ‘“â†’ğ‘‹â„¤ğµğ‘‚f\colon X\rightarrow\mathbb{Z}\times BO in such a way that uses the Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-structure on â„¤Ã—Bâ€‹Oâ„¤ğµğ‘‚\mathbb{Z}\times BO. They use this for orientation theory and relate Gâ€‹L1Wğºsuperscriptsubscriptğ¿1ğ‘ŠGL_{1}^{W}-orientations to logarithmic structures. They provide an Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-Thom isomorphism that allows to compute the homology of spectra appearing in connection with logarithmic ring spectra [108, Â§Â§â€‰ 7,8].

5. Constructing commutative ring spectra from bipermutative categories

In section 4 we saw that Thom spectra give rise to commutative ring spectra. Algebraic K-theory is another machine that takes a commutative ring (spectrum) Rğ‘…R and produces a commutative ring spectrum Kâ€‹(R)ğ¾ğ‘…K(R). In this section we focus on a classical construction that takes a small bipermutative category â„›â„›\mathcal{R} and turns it into a commutative ring spectrum. This construction goes back to Segal [114]; its multiplicative properties were investigated by May [81, 82, 83, 84], Shimada-Shimakawa [115], Woolfson [124] and Elmendorf-Mandell [35].

We sketch a simplified version of the construction, present some important examples and refer to [35] for a discussion of the multiplicative properties.

Remark 5.3.

6. From topological Hochschild to topological AndrÃ©-Quillen homology

For rings and algebras Hochschild homology contains a lot of information. For commutative rings and algebras AndrÃ©-Quillen homology is the adequate tool. There are spectrum level versions of these homology theories: topological Hochschild homology, ğ–³ğ–§ğ–§ğ–³ğ–§ğ–§\mathsf{THH}, and topological AndrÃ©-Quillen homology, ğ–³ğ– ğ–°ğ–³ğ– ğ–°\mathsf{TAQ}.

We can determine classes in the algebraic K-theory of a ring spectrum using the trace to topological Hochschild homology or to topological cyclic homology:

(6.1) tâ€‹r:Kâ€‹(R)â†’ğ–³ğ–§ğ–§â€‹(R).:ğ‘¡ğ‘Ÿâ†’ğ¾ğ‘…ğ–³ğ–§ğ–§ğ‘…tr\colon K(R)\rightarrow\mathsf{THH}(R).

For instance the trace from Kâ€‹(â„¤)ğ¾â„¤K(\mathbb{Z}) to ğ–³ğ–§ğ–§â€‹(â„¤)ğ–³ğ–§ğ–§â„¤\mathsf{THH}(\mathbb{Z}) detects important classes. BÃ¶kstedt, Madsen and Rognes [26, 103] show for instance that

tr:K2â€‹pâˆ’1â€‹(â„¤)â†’ğ–³ğ–§ğ–§2â€‹pâˆ’1â€‹(â„¤)â‰…â„¤/pâ€‹â„¤:trâ†’subscriptğ¾2ğ‘1â„¤subscriptğ–³ğ–§ğ–§2ğ‘1â„¤â„¤ğ‘â„¤\text{tr}\colon K_{2p-1}(\mathbb{Z})\rightarrow\mathsf{THH}_{2p-1}(\mathbb{Z})\cong\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}

is surjective for all primes pğ‘p.

We give a construction of topological Hochschild homology and more generally, for commutative ring spectra Rğ‘…R we define XâŠ—Rtensor-productğ‘‹ğ‘…X\otimes R for Xğ‘‹X a finite pointed simplicial set. We give some examples of calculations of such Xğ‘‹X-homology groups of Rğ‘…R and tell you about topological Hochschild cohomology as a derived center of an algebra spectrum. We define topological AndrÃ©-Quillen homology and we will see applications to Postnikov towers for commutative ring spectra later in 7.

6.4. Topological Hochschild cohomology as a derived center

In the discrete case, i.e., for a commutative ring kğ‘˜k and a kğ‘˜k-algebra Ağ´A one can describe the center of Ağ´A,

Zâ€‹(A)={bâˆˆA,aâ€‹b=bâ€‹aâ€‹Â for allÂ â€‹aâˆˆA}ğ‘ğ´formulae-sequenceğ‘ğ´ğ‘ğ‘ğ‘ğ‘Â for allÂ ğ‘ğ´Z(A)=\{b\in A,ab=ba\text{ for all }a\in A\}

as the set of Ağ´A-bimodule maps from Ağ´A to Ağ´A. If fğ‘“f is such a map, f:Aâ†’A:ğ‘“â†’ğ´ğ´f\colon A\rightarrow A with fâ€‹(câ€‹aâ€‹d)=câ€‹fâ€‹(a)â€‹dğ‘“ğ‘ğ‘ğ‘‘ğ‘ğ‘“ğ‘ğ‘‘f(cad)=cf(a)d for all a,c,dâˆˆAğ‘ğ‘ğ‘‘ğ´a,c,d\in A, then fğ‘“f is determined by f(1)=:bf(1)=:b and this bğ‘b satisfies

aâ€‹b=aâ€‹fâ€‹(1)=fâ€‹(aâ‹…1)=fâ€‹(a)=fâ€‹(1â‹…a)=fâ€‹(1)â€‹a=bâ€‹ağ‘ğ‘ğ‘ğ‘“1ğ‘“â‹…ğ‘1ğ‘“ğ‘ğ‘“â‹…1ğ‘ğ‘“1ğ‘ğ‘ğ‘ab=af(1)=f(a\cdot 1)=f(a)=f(1\cdot a)=f(1)a=ba

so the set of such morphisms gives rise to an element in the center and vice versa, for any bâˆˆZâ€‹(A)ğ‘ğ‘ğ´b\in Z(A) we get such an fğ‘“f by setting fâ€‹(1)=bğ‘“1ğ‘f(1)=b.

Hochschild cohomology of Ağ´A over kğ‘˜k can be described as

ğ–§ğ–§kâˆ—â€‹(A)=ğ–¤ğ—‘ğ—AâŠ—kAoâˆ—â€‹(A,A)subscriptsuperscriptğ–§ğ–§ğ‘˜ğ´subscriptsuperscriptğ–¤ğ—‘ğ—subscripttensor-productğ‘˜ğ´superscriptğ´ğ‘œğ´ğ´\mathsf{HH}^{*}_{k}(A)=\mathsf{Ext}^{*}_{A\otimes_{k}A^{o}}(A,A)

if Ağ´A is kğ‘˜k-projective. Hence ğ–§ğ–§k0â€‹(A)=Zâ€‹(A)subscriptsuperscriptğ–§ğ–§0ğ‘˜ğ´ğ‘ğ´\mathsf{HH}^{0}_{k}(A)=Z(A) and the Hochschild cohomology of Ağ´A is the derived center of Ağ´A. Hochschild cohomology has a graded commutative algebra structure via a cup product, but the solved Deligne conjecture [87] says that the Hochschild cochain complex is in general not a differential graded commutative algebra, but that it has an E2subscriptğ¸2E_{2}-algebra structure.

For ring spectra there is no homotopically meaningful definition of a center: requiring equality translates to an equalizer diagram and this wouldnâ€™t be homotopy invariant. For a commutative ring spectrum Rğ‘…R and an Rğ‘…R-algebra spectrum Ağ´A this equalizer corresponds precisely to taking not just Rğ‘…R-module endomorphisms but Ağ´A-bimodule endomorphisms. So a homotopy invariant version is as follows.

Definition 6.10.

For a commutative ring spectrum Rğ‘…R and an Rğ‘…R-algebra spectrum Ağ´A, the topological Hochschild cohomology groups of Ağ´A over Rğ‘…R are

ğ–³ğ–§ğ–§Râˆ—â€‹(A)=Ï€âˆ—â€‹ğ–¤ğ—‘ğ—Aâˆ§RAoâ€‹(A,A)superscriptsubscriptğ–³ğ–§ğ–§ğ‘…ğ´subscriptğœ‹subscriptğ–¤ğ—‘ğ—subscriptğ‘…ğ´superscriptğ´ğ‘œğ´ğ´\mathsf{THH}_{R}^{*}(A)=\pi_{*}\mathsf{Ext}_{A\wedge_{R}A^{o}}(A,A)

7. How do we recognize ring spectra as being (non) commutative?

If you have a concrete model of a homotopy type, say in symmetric spectra, then you can be lucky and this model posseses a commutative structure and you should be able to check this by hand. Of course you could also try to disprove commutativity by showing that your spectrum doesnâ€™t have power operations as in (2.2) and this has been done in many cases, but sometimes you might need a different approach.

7.1. Obstructions via filtrations and resolutions

An obstruction theory for Aâˆsubscriptğ´A_{\infty}-structures on homotopy ring spectra was developed as early as 1989 [100] by Alan Robinson. Obstruction theories for Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-structures came much later: Goerss-Hopkins and Robinson [38], [101] independently developed one with obstruction groups that later turned out to be isomorphic [19]. The idea is to use a filtration or resolution of an operad such that the corresponding filtration quotients or the corresponding spectral sequence gives rise to obstruction groups that contain obstructions for lifting a partial structure to a full Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-ring structure [101, Theorem 5.6], [38, Corollary 5.9]. The Goerss-Hopkins approach also allows to calculate the homotopy groups of the derived Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty} mapping space between two such Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-ring spectra [38, Theorem 4.5].

The obstruction groups have as input the algebra of cooperations Eâˆ—â€‹Esubscriptğ¸ğ¸E_{*}E of a spectrum Eğ¸E and they compute AndrÃ©-Quillen cohomology groups of the graded commutative Eâˆ—subscriptğ¸E_{*}-algebra Eâˆ—â€‹Esubscriptğ¸ğ¸E_{*}E in the setting of differential graded (or simplicial) Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-algebras. See [73], [39, Â§2.4] for background on these cohomology groups and see [19, Â§2] for the comparison results. In Robinsonâ€™s setting these groups are called Gamma-cohomology. The obstruction groups vanish if for instance Eâˆ—â€‹Esubscriptğ¸ğ¸E_{*}E is Ã©tale as an Eâˆ—subscriptğ¸E_{*}-algebra.

If you prefer to work with explicit chain complexes, then there are several equivalent ones computing Gamma cohomology groups in Robinsonâ€™s setting [101, Â§2.5], [102, Â§6], [93, Â§2] and therefore, by the comparison result from [19, Theorem 2.6], computing the obstruction groups in the Goerss-Hopkins setting as well.

There is another version of obstruction theory for promoting a homotopy Tğ‘‡T-algebra structure to an actual one by Johnson and Noel [58] where Tğ‘‡T is a monad. This includes obstructions for operadic structures on spectra but also includes for instance group actions. Noel shows that in certain situations the obstruction theory [58] can be compared to the one of [38].

We list some important applications:

  1. (a)

    The development of the Hopkins-Miller and Goerss-Hopkins obstruction theory was motivated by the Morava-Eğ¸E-theory spectra, also known as Lubin-Tate spectra, Ensubscriptğ¸ğ‘›E_{n} and variants of those. These are Landweber exact cohomology theories that govern the deformation theory of height nğ‘›n formal group laws. In [97] an obstruction theory was established that allowed to show that the Ensubscriptğ¸ğ‘›E_{n} are Aâˆsubscriptğ´A_{\infty} spectra and that the Morava stabilizer group ğ”¾nsubscriptğ”¾ğ‘›\mathbb{G}_{n} acts on Ensubscriptğ¸ğ‘›E_{n} via maps of Aâˆsubscriptğ´A_{\infty} spectra. In [38] the corresponding obstruction theory for Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-structures was developed and [38, Corollaries 7.6, 7.7] shows that the ğ”¾nsubscriptğ”¾ğ‘›\mathbb{G}_{n}-action is via Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-maps.

  2. (b)

    It was known that ğ¾ğ‘ˆğ¾ğ‘ˆ\mathit{KU} and ğ¾ğ‘‚ğ¾ğ‘‚\mathit{KO} are Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-spectra and it was also known that the pğ‘p-completed Adams summand Lpsubscriptğ¿ğ‘L_{p} is Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}. In [12] Andy Baker and I use Robinsonâ€™s version of the Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-obstruction theory to show that these Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-structures are unique and that the pğ‘p-local Adams summand also has a unique Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-structure. Uniqueness also holds for the connective covers [14]. It is important to have uniqueness results for Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-structures because calculations can depend on a choice of such a structure.

  3. (c)

    For an Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-ring spectrum Rğ‘…R there is a Î¸ğœƒ\theta-algebra structure on its pğ‘p-adic K-theory, Ï€âˆ—â€‹LKâ€‹(1)â€‹(Kâ€‹Upâˆ§R)subscriptğœ‹subscriptğ¿ğ¾1ğ¾subscriptğ‘ˆğ‘ğ‘…\pi_{*}L_{K(1)}(KU_{p}\wedge R) [39, Theorem 2.2.4] and in good cases

    Ï€âˆ—â€‹LKâ€‹(1)â€‹(Kâ€‹Upâˆ§R)â‰…limk(Kâ€‹Up)âˆ—â€‹(Râˆ§Mâ€‹(pk))subscriptğœ‹subscriptğ¿ğ¾1ğ¾subscriptğ‘ˆğ‘ğ‘…subscriptğ‘˜subscriptğ¾subscriptğ‘ˆğ‘ğ‘…ğ‘€superscriptğ‘ğ‘˜\pi_{*}L_{K(1)}(KU_{p}\wedge R)\cong\lim_{k}(KU_{p})_{*}(R\wedge M(p^{k}))

    where Mâ€‹(pk)ğ‘€superscriptğ‘ğ‘˜M(p^{k}) is the mod-pksuperscriptğ‘ğ‘˜p^{k} Moore spectrum. The study of such structures was initiated by McClure in [28, Chapter IX]. There is a variant of the Goerss-Hopkins obstruction theory for realizing for instance a Î¸ğœƒ\theta-algebra (see [39, Â§2.4.4] and [63, Theorem 5.14]) as a Kâ€‹(1)ğ¾1K(1)-local Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-ring spectrum.

    There is one for realizing an Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-Hâ€‹kğ»ğ‘˜H\!k-algebra spectrum with a fixed Dyer-Lashof structure on its homotopy [91, Proposition 2.2] (for kğ‘˜k a field of characteristic pğ‘p). Other variants can be found in the literature.

    The Î¸ğœƒ\theta-algebra version was successfully applied by Lawson and Naumann [63] to show that ğµğ‘ƒâ€‹âŸ¨2âŸ©ğµğ‘ƒdelimited-âŸ¨âŸ©2\mathit{BP}\langle 2\rangle at 222 has an Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-structure. By a different method Hill and Lawson [46, Theorem 4.2] find a commutative model for ğµğ‘ƒâ€‹âŸ¨2âŸ©ğµğ‘ƒdelimited-âŸ¨âŸ©2\mathit{BP}\langle 2\rangle at the prime 333.

  4. (d)

    Mathew, Naumann and Noel use operations in Morava-Eğ¸E-theory to prove Mayâ€™s nilpotence conjecture:

    Theorem 7.1.

    They use this â€“ among many other applications â€“ for the following result about Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-ring spectra:

    Lawson observed that using Kâ€‹(n)ğ¾ğ‘›K(n)-techniques (see [96] for background) this implies that for finite Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-ring spectra Rğ‘…R either the rational homology is non-trivial or Rğ‘…R is weakly contractible, because if Hâˆ—â€‹(R;â„š)â‰…0subscriptğ»ğ‘…â„š0H_{*}(R;\mathbb{Q})\cong 0, then by the above result all the Morava K-theories also vanish on Rğ‘…R, but then the finiteness of Rğ‘…R implies weak contractibility (see [79, Remark 4.3] for the full argument).

The Dyer-Lashof variant is for instance important when one wants to decide whether a given Hâˆsubscriptğ»H_{\infty}-map can be upgraded to an Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-map: Roughly speaking, an Hâˆsubscriptğ»H_{\infty}-spectrum is like an Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-spectrum in the homotopy category. Other spectra, for instance, ğµğ‘ƒğµğ‘ƒ\mathit{BP}, come with homology operations just because they sit in the right place: analyzing the maps ğ‘€ğ‘ˆâ†’ğµğ‘ƒâ†’Hâ€‹ğ”½pâ†’ğ‘€ğ‘ˆğµğ‘ƒâ†’ğ»subscriptğ”½ğ‘\mathit{MU}\rightarrow\mathit{BP}\rightarrow H\mathbb{F}_{p} gives [28, p.Â 63] that (Hâ€‹ğ”½p)âˆ—â€‹(ğµğ‘ƒ)subscriptğ»subscriptğ”½ğ‘ğµğ‘ƒ(H\mathbb{F}_{p})_{*}(\mathit{BP}) embeds into the dual of the Steenrod algebra such that (Hâ€‹ğ”½p)âˆ—â€‹(ğµğ‘ƒ)subscriptğ»subscriptğ”½ğ‘ğµğ‘ƒ(H\mathbb{F}_{p})_{*}(\mathit{BP}) is closed under the action of the Dyer-Lashof algebra â€“ even without establishing a structured multiplication on ğµğ‘ƒğµğ‘ƒ\mathit{BP}. This led Lawson [61] to look for the right obstructions for an Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-structure of ğµğ‘ƒğµğ‘ƒ\mathit{BP} at 222 via secondary operations (see Theorem 7.5).

7.3. Realization of Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-spectra via derived algebraic geometry

There is a completely different important and highly successful approach to realization problems, namely using derived algebraic geometry. You can learn about derived algebraic geometry in the next Chapter of the book.

8. What are Ã©tale maps?

We first recall the algebraic notion of an Ã©tale kğ‘˜k-algebra from [67, E.1]: Let kğ‘˜k be a commutative ring and let Ağ´A be a finitely generated commutative kğ‘˜k-algebra. Then Ağ´A is Ã©tale, if Ağ´A is flat over kğ‘˜k and if the module of KÃ¤hler differentials Î©A|k1subscriptsuperscriptÎ©1conditionalğ´ğ‘˜\Omega^{1}_{A|k} is trivial. If Î©A|k1=0subscriptsuperscriptÎ©1conditionalğ´ğ‘˜0\Omega^{1}_{A|k}=0, then kâ†’Aâ†’ğ‘˜ğ´k\rightarrow A is called unramified. A kğ‘˜k-algebra BğµB (not necessarily commutative) is called separable, if the multiplication map

BâŠ—kBoâ†’Bâ†’subscripttensor-productğ‘˜ğµsuperscriptğµğ‘œğµB\otimes_{k}B^{o}\rightarrow B

has a section as a BğµB-bimodule map. In algebra, a commutative separable algebra has Hochschild homology concentrated in homological degree zero, in particular the module of KÃ¤hler differentials is trivial.

8.1. Rognesâ€™ Galois extensions of commutative ring spectra

Definition 8.1.

[104, Definition 4.1.3] â€‰ Let Aâ†’Bâ†’ğ´ğµA\rightarrow B be a map of commutative ring spectra and let GğºG be a finite group acting on BğµB via commutative Ağ´A-algebra maps. Galois extensions of commutative ring spectra can have rather bad properties as modules. So the following definition is actually an additional assumption (this does not happen in the discrete setting).

Definition 8.2.

[104, Definition 4.3.1] A Galois extension Aâ†’Bâ†’ğ´ğµA\rightarrow B is faithful if it is faithful as an Ağ´A-module, i.e., for every Ağ´A-module Mğ‘€M with Mâˆ§ABâ‰ƒâˆ—similar-to-or-equalssubscriptğ´ğ‘€ğµM\wedge_{A}B\simeq* we have Mâ‰ƒâˆ—similar-to-or-equalsğ‘€M\simeq*.

8.3. Versions of Ã©tale descent

Transferring the Geller-Weibel result to the setting of commutative ring spectra, it seems natural to define two versions of descent:

Akhil Mathew clarifies the relationship between the different notions of Ã©tale morphisms and the notions of descent. Remark 8.11.

In [30] Clausen, Mathew, Naumann and Noel prove far-reaching Galois descent results for topological Hochschild homology and algebraic K-theory; in particular they confirm a Galois descent conjecture for algebraic K-theory by Ausoni and Rognes in many important cases. 9. Picard and Brauer groups

9.1. Picard groups in the setting of a symmetric monoidal category

Let (ğ’,âŠ—,1,Ï„)ğ’tensor-product1ğœ(\mathcal{C},\otimes,1,\tau) be a symmetric monoidal category. An important class of objects in ğ’ğ’\mathcal{C} are those objects Cğ¶C that have an inverse with respect to âŠ—tensor-product\otimes, i.e., there is an object Câ€²superscriptğ¶â€²C^{\prime} of ğ’ğ’\mathcal{C} such that

CâŠ—Câ€²â‰…1.tensor-productğ¶superscriptğ¶â€²1C\otimes C^{\prime}\cong 1.

One wants to gather such objects in a category and build a space and spectrum out of them:

Definition 9.1.

The Picard groupoid of ğ’ğ’\mathcal{C}, ğ–¯ğ—‚ğ–¼ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–½â€‹(ğ’)ğ–¯ğ—‚ğ–¼ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–½ğ’\mathsf{Picard}(\mathcal{C}), is the category whose objects are the invertible objects of ğ’ğ’\mathcal{C} and whose morphisms are isomorphisms between invertible objects.

In general, this category might not be small. Note that if C1subscriptğ¶1C_{1} and C2subscriptğ¶2C_{2} are objects of ğ–¯ğ—‚ğ–¼ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–½â€‹(ğ’)ğ–¯ğ—‚ğ–¼ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–½ğ’\mathsf{Picard}(\mathcal{C}), then so is C1âŠ—C2tensor-productsubscriptğ¶1subscriptğ¶2C_{1}\otimes C_{2}; in fact, ğ–¯ğ—‚ğ–¼ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–½â€‹(ğ’)ğ–¯ğ—‚ğ–¼ğ–ºğ—‹ğ–½ğ’\mathsf{Picard}(\mathcal{C}) is itself a symmetric monoidal category.

Definition 9.2.

The Picard group of ğ’ğ’\mathcal{C}, ğ–¯ğ—‚ğ–¼â€‹(ğ’)ğ–¯ğ—‚ğ–¼ğ’\mathsf{Pic}(\mathcal{C}), is Ï€0â€‹ğ–¯ğ–¨ğ–¢â€‹(ğ’)subscriptğœ‹0ğ–¯ğ–¨ğ–¢ğ’\pi_{0}\mathsf{PIC}(\mathcal{C}).

If the Picard groupoid of ğ’ğ’\mathcal{C} is small, then the Picard group can also be described as the set of isomorphism classes of invertible objects of ğ’ğ’\mathcal{C} with the product

[C1]âŠ—[C2]:=[C1âŠ—C2].assigntensor-productdelimited-[]subscriptğ¶1delimited-[]subscriptğ¶2delimited-[]tensor-productsubscriptğ¶1subscriptğ¶2[C_{1}]\otimes[C_{2}]:=[C_{1}\otimes C_{2}].

The neutral element is the isomorphism class of the unit, [1]delimited-[]1[1].

Definition 9.3.

Let Rğ‘…R be a (discrete) commutative ring, then we denote by ğ–¯ğ—‚ğ–¼â€‹(R)ğ–¯ğ—‚ğ–¼ğ‘…\mathsf{Pic}(R) the Picard group of the symmetric monoidal category of the category of Rğ‘…R-modules and by ğ–¯ğ–¨ğ–¢â€‹(R)ğ–¯ğ–¨ğ–¢ğ‘…\mathsf{PIC}(R) (and ğ—‰ğ—‚ğ–¼â€‹(R)ğ—‰ğ—‚ğ–¼ğ‘…\mathsf{pic}(R)) the Picard space (and Picard spectrum) of this category.

For instance the Picard group of a ring of integers in a number ring is its ideal class group.

9.2. Picard group for commutative ring spectra

For commutative ring spectra Rğ‘…R, the above definition of ğ–¯ğ–¨ğ–¢â€‹(R)ğ–¯ğ–¨ğ–¢ğ‘…\mathsf{PIC}(R) and ğ—‰ğ—‚ğ–¼â€‹(R)ğ—‰ğ—‚ğ–¼ğ‘…\mathsf{pic}(R) would either be much too rigid (if one would choose ğ’ğ’\mathcal{C} to be the category of Rğ‘…R-module spectra and isomorphisms) or not strict enough (if one would take ğ’ğ’\mathcal{C} to be the homotopy category of Rğ‘…R-module spectra). See [80, Â§2] for an adequate background for a suitable definition and see [36, Â§4] for a dictionary how to pass from a commutative ring spectrum Rğ‘…R and its category of modules to the âˆ\infty-categorical setting. Instead of working with symmetric monoidal categories, one uses presentable symmetric monoidal âˆ\infty-categories ğ’ğ’\mathcal{C}. Then the Picard âˆ\infty-groupoid of ğ’ğ’\mathcal{C} is the maximal subgroupoid of the underlying âˆ\infty-category of ğ’ğ’\mathcal{C} spanned by the invertible objects. This groupoid is equivalent to a grouplike Eâˆsubscriptğ¸E_{\infty}-space ğ–¯ğ–¨ğ–¢â€‹(ğ’)ğ–¯ğ–¨ğ–¢ğ’\mathsf{PIC}(\mathcal{C}) and hence there is a connective ring spectrum, ğ—‰ğ—‚ğ–¼â€‹(ğ’)ğ—‰ğ—‚ğ–¼ğ’\mathsf{pic}(\mathcal{C}), associated to ğ’ğ’\mathcal{C} [36, Â§5].

Let Rğ‘…R be a commutative ring spectrum. The operadic nerve of the category of cofibrant-fibrant Rğ‘…R-modules is a stable presentable symmetric monoidal âˆ\infty-category [69, Proposition 4.1.3.10] and we will abbreviate this as the âˆ\infty-category of Rğ‘…R-modules, Râ€‹modğ‘…modR\text{mod}.

Definition 9.4.

The Picard group of a commutative ring spectrum Rğ‘…R, ğ–¯ğ—‚ğ–¼â€‹(R)ğ–¯ğ—‚ğ–¼ğ‘…\mathsf{Pic}(R), is the group Ï€0â€‹(ğ–¯ğ–¨ğ–¢â€‹(Râ€‹mod))subscriptğœ‹0ğ–¯ğ–¨ğ–¢ğ‘…mod\pi_{0}(\mathsf{PIC}(R\text{mod})).

9.4. Brauer groups of commutative rings

Probably most of you will know the definition of the Brauer group of a field. But as for many features that we want to transfer to the spectral world we need to consider algebraic concepts developed for commutative rings (not fields).

Azumaya started to think about general Brauer groups [10] in the setting of local rings. A general definition of the Brauer group of a commutative ring Rğ‘…R was given by Auslander and Goldman [8] as Morita equivalence classes of Azumaya algebras. The Brauer group was then globalized to schemes by Grothendieck [43]. He also shows that the Brauer group of the initial ring â„¤â„¤\mathbb{Z} is trivial; this is a byproduct of his identification of Brauer groups of number rings in [43, III, Proposition (2.4)].

9.5. Brave new Brauer groups

Baker and Lazarev define in [11] what an Azumaya algebra spectrum is. We use one version of this definition in [15] to develop Brauer groups for commutative ring spectra. Related concepts can be found in [57] and [121].

Fix a cofibrant commutative ring spectrum Rğ‘…R.

Definition 9.8.

A cofibrant associative Rğ‘…R-algebra Ağ´A is called an Azumaya Rğ‘…R-algebra spectrum if Ağ´A is dualizable and faithful as an Rğ‘…R-module spectrum and if the canonical map

Aâˆ§RAoâ†’FRâ€‹(A,A)â†’subscriptğ‘…ğ´superscriptğ´ğ‘œsubscriptğ¹ğ‘…ğ´ğ´A\wedge_{R}A^{o}\rightarrow F_{R}(A,A)

is a weak equivalence.

We list some crucial properties of Azumaya algebra spectra. For the first property recall the discussion of derived centers from Definition 6.10.

Proposition 9.9.
  2. (a)

Thus the endomorphism Azumaya algebras are the ones that are always there and you want to ignore them.

Definition 9.10.

Let Ağ´A and BğµB be two Azumaya Rğ‘…R-algebra spectra. We call them Brauer equivalent if there are dualizable, faithful Rğ‘…R-modules Nğ‘N and Mğ‘€M such that there is an Rğ‘…R-algebra equivalence

Johnson shows [57, Lemma 5.7] that one can reduce the above relation to what he calls Eilenberg-Watts equivalence. We showed a Galois descent result [15, Proposition 3.2], saying that under some natural condition you can descent an Azumaya algebra Cğ¶C over BğµB to an Azumaya algebra Châ€‹Gsuperscriptğ¶â„ğºC^{hG} over Ağ´A is Aâ†’Bâ†’ğ´ğµA\rightarrow B is a faithful GğºG-Galois extension with finite Galois group GğºG.

They also construct a map of âˆ\infty-groupoids Aâ€‹zRâ†’Bâ€‹rRâ†’ğ´subscriptğ‘§ğ‘…ğµsubscriptğ‘Ÿğ‘…Az_{R}\rightarrow Br_{R} for any commutative ring spectrum Rğ‘…R and show that this map is essentially surjective, such that equality in Ï€0â€‹(Bâ€‹rR)subscriptğœ‹0ğµsubscriptğ‘Ÿğ‘…\pi_{0}(Br_{R}) corresponds precisely to Morita equivalence. They investigate the algebraic Brauer groups (i.e., the Morita classes of Azumaya algebras over the coefficients) [36, Â§7.1] of 222-periodic commutative ring spectra with vanishing odd homotopy groups, such as ğ¾ğ‘ˆğ¾ğ‘ˆ\mathit{KU} or Ensubscriptğ¸ğ‘›E_{n}, by relating them to the classical Brauer-Wall group of Ï€0subscriptğœ‹0\pi_{0} of the ring spectrum and they identify a non-trivial Morita class of a quaternion ğ¾ğ‘‚ğ¾ğ‘‚\mathit{KO}-algebra that becomes Morita-trivial over ğ¾ğ‘ˆğ¾ğ‘ˆ\mathit{KU}.

There is recent work by Hopkins and Lurie [50] who identify the Kâ€‹(n)ğ¾ğ‘›K(n)-local Brauer group of a Lubin-Tate spectrum Eğ¸E at all primes. For odd primes they obtain:

Theorem 9.13.

[50, Theorem 1.0.11] â€‰ The Kâ€‹(n)ğ¾ğ‘›K(n)-local Brauer group of Eğ¸E is the product of the Brauer-Wall group of the residue field Ï€0â€‹(E)/msubscriptğœ‹0ğ¸ğ‘š\pi_{0}(E)/m and a group Bâ€‹râ€²â€‹(E)ğµsuperscriptğ‘Ÿâ€²ğ¸Br^{\prime}(E) which in turn can be expressed as an inverse limit of abelian groups Bâ€‹râ„“â€²ğµsubscriptsuperscriptğ‘Ÿâ€²â„“Br^{\prime}_{\ell} such that the kernel of Bâ€‹râ„“â€²â†’Bâ€‹râ„“âˆ’1â€²â†’ğµsubscriptsuperscriptğ‘Ÿâ€²â„“ğµsubscriptsuperscriptğ‘Ÿâ€²â„“1Br^{\prime}_{\ell}\rightarrow Br^{\prime}_{\ell-1} is non-canonically isomorphic to mâ„“+2/mâ„“+3superscriptğ‘šâ„“2superscriptğ‘šâ„“3m^{\ell+2}/m^{\ell+3}.

One ingredient is their construction of atomic Eğ¸E-algebra spectra [50, Definition 1.0.2] via a Thom spectrum construction relative to Eğ¸E for polarizations of lattices [50, Definition 3.2.1] using the machinery from [1, 2].
